, that lies are not protected by free speech, that police subvert their mission when they lie to suspects, and that scholars undermine their goals when they lie to research subjects.Many philosophers start to craft moral exceptions to demands for sincerity and fidelity when they confront wrongdoers, the pressures of non-ideal circumstances, or the achievement of morally substantial ends. But Shiffrin consistently resists this sort of exceptionalism, arguing that maintaining a strong basis for trust and reliable communication through practices of sincerity, fidelity, and respecting free speech is an essential aspect of ensuring the conditions for moral progress, including our rehabilitation of and moral reconciliation with wrongdoers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aFreedom of speech. 0aTruthfulness and falsehood. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAdam Smith.  aImmanuel Kant.  aMurderer at the Door.  aStolen Valor Act.  aUnited States v. Alvarez.  aacademic freedom.  aacademic research.  aaccommodation.  aautobiographical lies.  acoercion.  acommunication.  acommunicative ethics.  acompelled disclosure.  acontent-discrimination.  acontracts.  adeception.  adiscursive communication.  aduress.  aequality.  afidelity.  afreedom of communication.  afreedom of speech.  afreedom of thought.  aharm.  ainstitutions.  alying.  amisrepresentation.  amoral agency.  amoral failure.  amoral imperfection.  amoral obligations.  amoral progress.  amoral wrongs.  amorality.  apromises.  apuffery.  aqualified absolutism.  aresearch subjects.  aself-definition.  asincerity.  athinker-based approach.  athird parties.  atruth.  auniversities.  awrongful deception.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Universi